<br>
First off, it wasn't a new medium.  By that time, movie-making was 50 years old.<br>
<br>
And how on Earth is it not original to create something that uses styles that are STILL emulated over 60 years later?  Your argument has huge holes in it.<br>
<br>
And no, not everyone was &quot;trying new things because they could&quot;.  In fact, it was almost the exact opposite.  Once again I state that you need to do a little more fact-checking before posting about film history.<br>
<br>
*And comparing it to the Mona Lisa is not a good analagy, because the Mona Lisa wasn't that creative, it was just a really good portrait, with some mystery around it. But when it comes down to it, it's a portarit, those have been being done for quite some time. And the Mona Lisa is more famous because of who did it, not because of what it was. *<br>
<br>
I admit that the Mona Lisa may not have been the best analogy to use in this situation but it illustrated my point just fine.  And my art history may be a little fuzzy on this, but did Da Vinci make the Mona Lisa famous or did the Mona Lisa make Da Vinci famous?  I would have to do a lot more research on the subject before claiming to know.<br>
<br>
But that's aside from the point.  You could place any number of hundreds of classic art pieces into my original statement and it would still ring true. <p>The surest sign of intelligent life in the universe is that none of it has tried contacting us.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thebraneatingzombie>The Bran Eating Zombie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(12/9/02 11:44:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11559.topic&index=54>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.marilynmanson.com/manson/images/portrait/portrait030.jpg length=180 width=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: gay movie makers</span><hr size=1> It was basically a new medium, when you compare it to all the other mediums out there. And according to your argument, the reason it is such a great movie, is everyone was using the exact same camera angles, then Orson Wells thought &quot;Hey, why not try some different camera angles&quot; and that made it one of the best movies ever made. And MY argument is the one with holes in it?<br>
